'''Keidai Toshi''' (境内都市) is a historical concept in {{ill|Japanese history|ja|日本史|12=draft|12=draft}}, referring to the characteristics of {{ill|urban areas|ja|都市|12=draft|12=draft}} during the {{ill|medieval period of Japan|ja|中世|12=draft|12=draft}} (roughly 12th to 16th centuries). It describes clusters of urban settlements centered around religious institutions such as {{ill|temples|ja|寺院|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|shrines|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}}.
The term "Keidai Toshi" was proposed by Japanese historian {{ill|Masatoshi Ito|ja|伊藤正敏|12=draft|12=draft}} and has since gained support among scholars. In his own work, Ito remarked, "Honestly, I don’t understand why I was the first to point this out."<ref>伊藤(2008), p. 91.</ref> He also expressed dissatisfaction with the term’s phrasing, stating, "The term doesn’t sound right," and hinted at the possibility of renaming it in the future.<ref>伊藤(2008), p. 247.</ref>
== Overview ==
Before the concept of "Keidai Toshi" was introduced, settlements originating from religious institutions were regarded as {{ill|Monzen-machi|ja|門前町|12=draft|12=draft}} (urban areas centered on commerce for worshippers). It was assumed that their primary function was religious, and their economic role was subordinate. Modern perceptions of religion as isolated from economic activities further reinforced the notion that Monzen-machi did not hold significant economic importance.
The concept of "Keidai Toshi" seeks to revise this perspective, suggesting that large settlements originating from religious institutions should be recognized as urban areas with political, cultural, industrial, and military functions.
The "Keidai Toshi" varied in scale, but the larger ones are thought to have had populations exceeding 100,000.<ref>伊藤(2008), p. 92.</ref> In medieval Japan, cities with tens of thousands of inhabitants were considered "large cities," contrasting sharply with the image of small settlements suggested by the term "Monzen-machi."
== Functions of Keidai Toshi ==
=== Political Function === Keidai Toshi were urban areas established based on large religious organizations such as major temples and shrines. These religious institutions formed a significant political force, known as {{ill|temple and shrine powers|ja|寺社勢力|12=draft|12=draft}}, rivaling the {{ill|Imperial Court (Japan)|ja|朝廷|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|samurai|ja|武家|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|shogunate|ja|幕府|12=draft|12=draft}}). Consequently, Keidai Toshi served as political centers of these religious authorities.
=== Cultural Function === As religious organizations often served as centers of learning in medieval Japan, Keidai Toshi played significant roles as cultural hubs. These "centers of learning" extended beyond religious studies to include practical disciplines such as martial arts, medicine, civil engineering, and agriculture. This cultural aspect contributed to the economic significance and growth of Keidai Toshi.
=== Economic Function === Keidai Toshi possessed advanced industrial production capabilities, supported by practical knowledge concentrated in these cities and skilled artisan groups associated with religious organizations. For example, records show that in 1360, {{ill|Hatakeyama Yoshifusa|ja|畠山義深|12=draft|12=draft}} urged {{ill|Negoro-ji|ja|根来寺|12=draft|12=draft}} to deliver shields and bows, and in 1584, {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|ja|徳川家康|12=draft|12=draft}} requested 500 muskets and warrior monks from {{ill|Mount Kōya|ja|高野山|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>Such activities demonstrate the role of prominent temples and shrines in the military-industrial complex of the time.</ref>
Moreover, Keidai Toshi functioned as key trade hubs, facilitated by the movement of pilgrims and other travelers.
=== Military Function === Keidai Toshi often held military significance. In addition to possessing strong military power based on economic strength and arms production, temples and shrines were sometimes designed and constructed as fortresses.<ref>The earliest medieval mountain fortress in Japan is said to be {{ill|Mount Hiei|ja|比叡山|12=draft|12=draft}}, built in 1166.</ref> They housed large numbers of {{ill|warrior monks|ja|僧兵|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Jinin|ja|神人|12=draft|12=draft}}, enabling independent military operations.
This military capability often made Keidai Toshi autonomous {{ill|asylums (law)|ja|アジール|12=draft|12=draft}} free from external control.
== Notes == <references/>
== References == * {{ill|Masatoshi Ito|ja|伊藤正敏|12=draft|12=draft}}, ''Jisha Seiryoku no Chūsei'' (寺社勢力の中世), Chikuma Shobō, 2008. ISBN 978-4-480-06435-6. == See Also == * {{ill|Temple and shrine powers|ja|寺社勢力|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Jinaimachi|ja|寺内町|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Right of asylum|ja|アジール権|fr|Droit d'asile|ja|アジール|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Yamashina Hongan-ji|ja|山科本願寺|12=draft|12=draft}} / {{ill|Ishiyama Hongan-ji|ja|石山本願寺|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Mount Kōya|ja|高野山|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Jinin|ja|神人|12=draft|12=draft}} / {{ill|Warrior monks|ja|僧兵|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Temple Precinct Cities|ja|境内都市|en|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Jinaimachi|fr|Jinaicho|ja|寺内町|lt=Teramachi|en|12=draft|12=draft}}
