Moreover, Keidai Toshi functioned as key trade hubs, facilitated by the movement of pilgrims and other travelers.

=== Military Function ===
Keidai Toshi often held military significance. In addition to possessing strong military power based on economic strength and arms production, temples and shrines were sometimes designed and constructed as fortresses.<ref>The earliest medieval mountain fortress in Japan is said to be {{ill|Mount Hiei|en|Mount Hiei|WD=Q748040|lt=Mount Hiei|1=Mount Hiei}}, built in 1166.</ref> They housed large numbers of {{ill|Sōhei|en|Sōhei|WD=Q1475695|lt=Warrior monks|1=Sōhei}} and {{ill|Jinin|ja|神人|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jinin|qq=}}, enabling independent military operations.

This military capability often made Keidai Toshi autonomous {{ill|asylums (law)|ja|アジール|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/asylums (law)|1=asylum|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q26377}} free from external control.

