==Merged second translation==
{{ill|Temple Precinct Cities|en|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Temple complexes as urban areas|qq=}}, functioned as proto-megalopolises.

'''Keidai Toshi''' (境内都市, *Keidai Toshi*) is a historical concept in [[:en:Japanese history|Japanese history]], referring to a type of {{ill|urban settlement|en|urban settlement|WD=Q7900166|lt=urban settlement|1=Urban settlement}} characteristic of the [[:en:Medieval period|Medieval period]] (12th to 16th century). It denotes cities that developed around religious facilities such as {{ill|Buddhist temples in Japan|en|Buddhist temples in Japan|WD=Q3141900|lt=Buddhist temples in Japan|1=Buddhist temples in Japan}} and [[:en:Shrines|Shrines]].

The term "Keidai Toshi" was proposed by Japanese historian {{ill|Masatoshi Ito|ja|伊藤正敏|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Masatoshi Ito|1=Itō Masatoshi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11380223}} and has since gained support among scholars. In his book, Ito noted, "To be honest, I don't understand why I was the first to point this out<ref>伊藤(2008), p. 91.</ref>." He also stated that he might consider changing the term in the future due to its perceived awkwardness<ref>伊藤(2008), p. 247.</ref>.

== Overview ==

Before this concept was introduced, settlements originating from temples and shrines were typically regarded as {{ill|Monzen-machi|lt=Monzen-machi|lt=Monzen-machi|ja|門前町|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Monzen-machi|qq=}}, or towns that engaged in commercial activities targeting worshippers. The prevailing view was that their primary function was religious, with economic functions considered secondary. Additionally, the modern notion that religion is separate from economics contributed to the perception that Monzen-machi lacked significant economic functions.

The concept of "Keidai Toshi" was proposed to revise these common perceptions. It redefines large settlements originating from temples and shrines as cities with complex functions, including political, cultural, industrial, and military roles.

While the scale of these "Keidai Toshi" varied, some are thought to have had populations exceeding 100,000<ref>伊藤(2008), p. 92.</ref>. In medieval Japan, a population of tens of thousands constituted a "metropolis," which contrasts sharply with the small-scale settlement image implied by the term Monzen-machi.

== Functions of Keidai Toshi ==

=== Political Function ===
Keidai Toshi were urban centers based on major religious organizations such as large temples and shrines. In medieval Japan, these religious institutions, alongside the {{ill|Royal court|en|Royal court|WD=Q1134237|lt=Imperial Court (Japan)|1=Royal court}} and warrior governments ({{ill|Bakufu|ja|幕府|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bakufu|comment=changed title based on wikidata|1=Shogunate|WD=Q1074150}}), formed a major political force known as {{ill|Temple and Shrine Powers|lt=Temple and Shrine Powers|lt=Temple and Shrine Power|ja|寺社勢力|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Temple and Shrine Power|qq=}}. As a result, Keidai Toshi functioned as political centers for these religious powers.

=== Cultural Function ===
Keidai Toshi were also hubs of cultural activity, as major temples and shrines served as places of learning with significant status in medieval Japan. These cities provided not only religious education but also practical knowledge in fields such as martial arts, medicine, civil engineering, and agriculture. This cultural function drove their development as major economic centers, beyond their political and religious significance.

=== Economic Function ===
Keidai Toshi maintained high levels of industrial production, supported by practical knowledge concentrated in these cities and by skilled occupational groups tied to religious organizations. For example, historical records indicate that prominent temples produced weapons and military supplies<ref>Examples include orders for shields and arrows at {{ill|Negoro-ji|en|Negoro-ji|WD=Q1552446|lt=Negoro-ji|1=Negoro-ji}} in 1360, requests for 500 rifles and warrior monks by {{ill|Tokugawa Ieyasu|en|Tokugawa Ieyasu|WD=Q171977|lt=Tokugawa Ieyasu|1=Tokugawa Ieyasu}} at {{ill|Mount Kōya|en|Mount Kōya|WD=Q535065|lt=Mount Koya|1=Mount Kōya}} in 1584, and Toyotomi Hideyoshi's prohibition of weapon manufacturing by temples in 1585.</ref>.

In addition to industrial production, Keidai Toshi also served as important trade hubs due to the movement of worshippers and other travelers.

=== Military Function ===
Many Keidai Toshi also had military functions. In addition to their economic power and production of military supplies, temples and shrines were often designed as fortifications<ref>The earliest medieval mountain fortress in Japan is said to be the {{ill|Enryaku-ji|ja|比叡山延暦寺|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Enryaku-ji|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 延暦寺}} on Mount Hiei, built in 1166.</ref>. They maintained significant military forces, including warrior monks ({{ill|Sōhei|en|Sōhei|WD=Q1475695|lt=Sohei|1=Sōhei}}) and shrine warriors ({{ill|Jinin|ja|神人|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jinin|qq=}}), and were capable of conducting independent military operations.

This military power often allowed Keidai Toshi to function as independent {{ill|Asylums|ja|アジール|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asylums|1=asylum|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q26377}}, free from external authority.

